Edith Picht-Axenfeld (Freiburg im Breisgau, 1 January 1914 – Hinterzarten, 19 April 2001) was a German pianist and harpsichordist.
She started her concert career in 1935, and took part two years later in the III International Chopin Piano Competition, when she was awarded the sixth prize; this launched her career.

Picht-Axenfeld married the professor for philosophy Georg Picht in 1936.
She taught at the Staatliche Hochschule für Musik in Freiburg im Breisgau from 1947 to 1979.
Her 1968 recording of the Goldberg Variations is often considered as a point of reference and there obviously is still a fan base that has uploaded many full albums to YouTube.
